com.android.dialogs

Class AlertDialogs

  • java.lang.Object
    • DialogFragment
      • com.android.dialogs.AlertDialogs
  • Direct Known Subclasses:
    CarouselIemFilterDialog, ScrollViewDialog

    public class AlertDialogs
extends DialogFragment
    Displays the basic version of the alert dialog box that contains text message. It can can consist of the following elements:
    • icon - is displayed in the upper left corner of the dialog (see TITLE_ICON_ID),
    • title - it is displayed to the right of the icon that was described above (see TITLE_ID),
    • message - text displayed in the dialog (see MESSAGE_ID).
    • button#1 - a positive button, which is usually responsible for the acceptance / confirmation / close dialog with a positive result (see POSITIVE_BUTTON_ID).
    • button#2 - a neutral button, which is usually responsible for the display of additional help / execution of custom commands in the dialog box (see NEUTRAL_BUTTON_ID).
    • button#3 - a negative button, which is usually responsible for the cancellation of all operations / refusal to grant permissions (see NEGATIVE_BUTTON_ID).
    In the absence of any component of the above, the dialog will not be created. Activity, which contains a dialog must implement ButtonsFocusChangeListener in order to receive signals from either positiveButton, neutralButton or negativeButton. Each activity, using dialog boxes, also should have befriended inner class (e.g. MainActivity.DialogList), which defines the values ​​of specific dialog boxes that are displayed in that activity. The values ​​that are common for many dialogs (such as button labels, dialog icons) are stored in DialogListCore class.
    Author:
    tomasz
    See Also:
    DialogListCore, DialogListCore#ID_TITLE_NO_TITLE, DialogListCore#ID_MESSAGE_NO_MESSAGE

      • buildDialogButtons

        public void buildDialogButtons(Builder builder,
                      DialogButtonClickListener eventListener)
        Part of onCreateDialog(Bundle) that creates dialog buttons. Creates a dialog buttons based on values:
        • POSITIVE_BUTTON_ID
        • NEUTRAL_BUTTON_ID
        • NEGATIVE_BUTTON_ID
        that was created in newInstance(Integer, Integer, Integer, Integer, Integer, Integer). In the key-value pairs (e.g. <POSITIVE_BUTTON_ID,0>) dialog button labels are stored. If the value of given key is not set - the button will not be created. Otherwise, the method will add DialogInterface.OnClickListener to the created buttons, which will execute appropriate method in eventListener each time user taps one of them.
        Parameters:
        builder - dialogBuilder that builds entire dialog window
        eventListener - activity that implements DialogButtonClickListener and will receive data from alert dialog

      • buildDialogContent

        public void buildDialogContent(Builder builder)
        Part of onCreateDialog(Bundle) that creates dialog message. Creates a dialog message based on value:
        • MESSAGE_ID
        that was created in newInstance(Integer, Integer, Integer, Integer, Integer, Integer). ID value that this method needs is stored in the key-value pair <MESSAGE_ID,X>, where X is that value.
        Parameters:
        builder - dialogBuilder that builds entire dialog window

      • showDialog

        public static void showDialog(Activity activity,
              java.lang.String dialogIDTag,
              java.lang.Integer titleIconID,
              java.lang.Integer titleID,
              java.lang.Integer messageID,
              java.lang.Integer positiveButtonID,
              java.lang.Integer neutralButtonID,
              java.lang.Integer negativeButtonID)
        Displays alert dialog in given Activity. Usage example: 
         AlertDialogs.showDialog(this,
                                                MultiplayExplorerActivity.DialogList.TAG_NO_CONNECTION_FOUND,
                                                DialogListCore.IT_TITLE_ICON_WARNING,
                                                MultiplayExplorerActivity.DialogList.ID_TITLE_NO_CONNECTION_FOUND,
                                                MultiplayExplorerActivity.DialogList.ID_MESSAGE_NO_CONNECTION_FOUND,
                                                DialogListCore.ID_BUTTON_OPTIONS,
                                                null,
                                                DialogListCore.ID_BUTTON_CANCEL);
        In the above code in this Activity dialog box is displayed, which is containing 2 of 3 buttons:
        • Positive button with label defined under DialogListCore.ID_BUTTON_OPTIONS,
        • Negative button with label defined under DialogListCore.ID_BUTTON_CANCEL.
        Neutral button will not be even displayed as null value is set.
        Parameters:
        activity - activity where dialog will be displayed
        dialogIDTag - a unique value to distinguish dialog boxes where more than one is displayed in one activity
        titleIconID - see newInstance(Integer, Integer, Integer, Integer, Integer, Integer) parameters
        titleID - see newInstance(Integer, Integer, Integer, Integer, Integer, Integer) parameters
        messageID - see newInstance(Integer, Integer, Integer, Integer, Integer, Integer) parameters
        positiveButtonID - see newInstance(Integer, Integer, Integer, Integer, Integer, Integer) parameters
        neutralButtonID - see newInstance(Integer, Integer, Integer, Integer, Integer, Integer) parameters
        negativeButtonID - see newInstance(Integer, Integer, Integer, Integer, Integer, Integer) parameters

      • onShow

        public void onShow(DialogInterface dialog)
        Assigns a reference to each of the dialog buttons. It is performed when the dialog box appears. Assigns button's references to variables positiveButton, neutralButton and positiveButton, so that later can be used (for example, to lock the keys in the event of failure of the data validation).
